    bio: "Austen Henry Layard was born in Paris to English parents and spent much of his youth travelling across Europe and the Middle East, developing an obsessive fascination with the ancient civilisations of Mesopotamia long before he possessed the resources or credentials to pursue them professionally. He first visited the mounds of Nimrud in modern Iraq in 1840, and the sight of weathered mud-brick rising from the desert plain convinced him that something extraordinary lay beneath. He spent years in poverty and diplomatic odd-jobs before securing modest funding from the British ambassador in Constantinople to begin excavating in 1845.\n\nWhat Layard found at Nimrud and later at Kuyunjik — the site of ancient Nineveh — exceeded even his most extravagant hopes. He unearthed the palace of Sennacherib and later the library of Ashurbanipal, recovering thousands of cuneiform tablets, enormous carved stone reliefs depicting royal hunts and military campaigns, and the famous winged bull colossi that now flank the entrance to the British Museum's Assyrian galleries. His popular accounts of the excavations, Nineveh and Its Remains (1849) and Discoveries in the Ruins of Nineveh and Babylon (1853), became Victorian bestsellers, awakening the British public to the depth and sophistication of Mesopotamian civilisation.\n\nLayard's methods were a product of his era — rapid, extractive, and largely unconcerned with the stratigraphic context that modern archaeology considers essential. Yet his energy, his gift for narrative, and his genuine sense of wonder at what he was uncovering gave Assyriology its founding mythology. He later shifted careers entirely, becoming a Liberal Member of Parliament, a diplomat of considerable skill, and eventually British Ambassador to the Ottoman Empire. He died in London in 1894, having spent his final decades collecting Venetian paintings — a quieter kind of excavation, but driven by the same insatiable curiosity that had first sent him into the Iraqi desert."
